    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1935651881" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1935651881" />
    <a title="Nancy Groves" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5624190-nancy-groves"><img alt="Nancy Groves" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1935651881?book_show_action=true">Mar 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nancy Groves" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nancy Groves" href="/user/show/5624190-nancy-groves">Nancy Groves</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1935651881" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9613710812610756219">The author of this book was Mrs. King&apos;s sister, a relationship that enabled her to describe her life with an intimacy and familiarity that no other writer could have achieved. She did an excellent job of showing how Mrs. King&apos;s beliefs and principles were shaped from early childhood and depicting quite clearly that Coretta was not just a wife joining her husband&apos;s cause but a woman who was an equal partner, pursuing the same goals of economic and social justice but often in her own way, for inst</span>
  <span id="freeText9613710812610756219" style="display:none">The author of this book was Mrs. King's sister, a relationship that enabled her to describe her life with an intimacy and familiarity that no other writer could have achieved. She did an excellent job of showing how Mrs. King's beliefs and principles were shaped from early childhood and depicting quite clearly that Coretta was not just a wife joining her husband's cause but a woman who was an equal partner, pursuing the same goals of economic and social justice but often in her own way, for instance by using the arts to reach hearts and minds and achieve change, and also becoming involved in an array of causes on her own. My only quibble is that following the chapters devoted to Dr. King's assassination, funeral, and the immediate aftermath, the handful of remaining chapters describe the next 30-some years of her life primarily by devoting a few sentences each to a series of meetings, speeches, accomplishments, and awards. Of course, to describe even a few of the events of those decades in detail would have resulted in a substantially longer book or much less attention to Mrs. King's formative childhood, youth, and early adulthood. I think that the focus on the earlier years is welcome in that it amply demonstrates that she was so much more than "Mrs. King," wife and mother, that she was not simply following along behind her husband, and that her life after his death was not merely dedicated to a continuation of his ideas. I'm sure that her later years are discussed in other biographies, which I may seek out to learn more about this remarkable woman.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9613710812610756219" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


